post_text:
On the 1st day of school, all students will meet with their respective teachers on the upper playground prior to entering the building. Drop-offs are welcome starting at 8 a.m. Upon arriving, we will direct students to their teachers. At 8.30 a.m. we will have a short welcome back message and review a few of the new expectations for this school year, including masks and temperature checks. We believe this will be a great way to welcome our students back and is the safest way to learn new procedures and find new classrooms!

Check out the details of the district's reopening plan via the following link:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1__IwzJ7tW-YDNlr21x5k7LXrRO-KuQVw/view

Only 4 sleeps until school!

Happy Wednesday, DES! ‚òÄÔ∏è

No video today because our bodies need the sun more than additional screen time.

Kids and Parents: How many of these emotion words resonate with you in this moment?
Any yellows out there? How‚Äôs about green? At this time, I‚Äôm a little of both..
Reds? Blues? Some of each?
All is ok. Your feelings are ok. üòä

For today, join me! Go snag your current or favorite book. Sit on the sun. Enjoy the moment. ‚òÄÔ∏è
üí°üìöü§ì What book is getting you outside today?

I‚Äôm thinking of you all! And, students, I continue to miss our M-F schedule like crazy. I love seeing you outside, though. Don‚Äôt mind my honks and big waves! üëãüèº üòÉ

Tonight, check in with each other before dinner.
..then check in again with each other in the morning.

& continue to check in with each other each day because our biggest emotional need is to be seen, to be heard and to be loved. (-Bren√© Brown)

Enjoy! ‚òÄÔ∏èüìö

Youuuu wanted to build a rainbow, so here it is!! üåà
Wow! This was fun!
In this activity we not only practice a form of Chromatography (separating out a mixture of chemicals), but we also bring in awareness of the Here & Now.

Ms. Sanger‚Äôs ‚ÄúColorful Emotions‚Äù lesson combines science & social emotional learning. WOWOWOW!
YAY!! I hope you have fun ü§ì

As always, I loooove seeing the end results, so post pictures in the comments! ‚ò∫Ô∏è

‚Ä¢absorbent paper towels (they recommend Bounty)
‚Ä¢5 washable markers (MUST be washable)
‚Ä¢2 small cups or jars

post_text: The Iditarod is over but the IDIDAREAD continues! If your child is reading at home, you can track their progress: 1,000 minutes (or 500 for Kindergarten and 1st) will earn them a snazzy, personalized Ididaread dogtag! You can use an official trail log from before break, tell me or your child's teacher if you want a new form, or just keep track with 100 tally marks on a paper. The important thing is that kids keep reading. I have enough for adults, too. Just let me know when you get to Nome and I will put your dogtag(s) in the next packet going out. ü¶∏‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èüìö

Dear Parents, Guardians, and Care Takers,
Staff will be working on putting together homework packets and getting them to families this week. In the mean time, we ask you to join us as we celebrate Mr. Tweet's 40th Birthday this week!

Each day there will be a new post with a fun little activity that involves Mr. Tweet. Any one can take part in these fun activities (Students, parents, community members), if you feel like posting your pictures and end results on the thread please do so. Each day we will take anyone who has participated and put their name into a drawing, we have books, beaver swag and other amazing prizes to give away!

DCSD Elementary School is Proud to Bring You - Team Hollywood Superhero Basketball!

When: Friday, October 25th from 6:00 - 7:30 P.M.

Please join us on Friday night in the Elementary School Gym for a fun-filled and memorable evening as our students will learn important skills about friendship, building positive relationships and treating each other with respect from Action Heroes!

Team Hollywood is an inspirational, funny and exciting group of former stars, athletes and all-around great people who travel across the country spreading joy, energy and life-lessons with students.

We look forward to seeing you and your children here for an extremely exciting evening.

Sincerely,

DCSD Staff

post_text:
Today @ DES we learned a lot about air quality. From what we learned today we think we will be better prepared for the next time it is smoky outside. Here are a few tools we discovered and want to pass on.

www.airvisual.com is a great website to see what the Air Quality Index (AQI) is. In larger districts when the AQI is above 100 they cancel outdoor events and have indoor recess. (At 7am in Dillingham this morning the AQI was 57. @ 9pm the AQI is 17.)

We also found a nice chart that talks about the levels of AQI. (attached to the post)

Our first priority at DES is children's safety. If you feel as a parent it is to smoky for your child at recess due to asthma or a recent cold/flu please call Ani or Mr. Schollmeier at 842 5642. We will have alternatives options for students who are extra sensitive to the smoke.
